In article <2jb4fp$kot@tornews.torolab.ibm.com>,
>
>   I think the best way to do this would be to have each user register his
>public key with the remailer when he joins up. The remailer also has 
>a public key.
>
>   When a sends to b, a encrypts the message with the remailer's public key.
>The remailer decrypts it, determines who the recipient is, and then 
>encrypts it with the recipients public key. Random length strings of garbage
>can be prepended to the message each way, and they can be batched up until 
>a certain number of them are ready to be transmitted -- in random order, of 
>course. 
>
	But that doesn't allow posting to newsgroups or other public forums
where the intent is only to hide the identity of the sender, not the
actual message.

